\subsubsection{Liquid-crystal display}:
\textbf{Theory}
The Hitachi HD44780-based 16x2 LCD is interfaced with the LPC4088 microcontroller using GPIO pins for data signals, control signals, and power connections (VCC and GND) \cite{hd44780-datasheet}. The microcontroller will send commands and data to the LCD in order to display the decoded output to the user.\\

\textbf{Implementation}
The LCD driver and its functions where used to perform the respective displays to the HD44780. An usigned short int was used to keep track of the cursor position on the 16*2 display. The initialize and use of the driver fucntions was done in the main file. For logic such as auto scrolling the use of lcd set cursor fucntions to move to the first line, clearing screen with lcd clear fucntion and priniting the previous second row with lcd print fucntion. All play a part in the functional and logical use of the lcd driver implementation.\\

The printStartMessage fucntion defined in the main class is a further implementation of printing to the lcd display. Here a pointer to a string of characters holding the message to be displayed is passed as a parameter. The use of the original lcd driver fucntions such as the clear and lcd print are used followed by a delay and clear of the display after the message has timed out.

\subsubsection{Feedback LEDs}:
\textbf{Theory}
Two LEDs connected through the GPIO pins will provide visual user feedback on the system state. A green LED will indicate that the system is in a safe defined state, whilst a red LED will indicate an error.\\

\emph{Note: All additional hardware components were sourced by the Computer Engineer through the electronics supplier 'Fabian Enterprises Ltd'}\\

\textbf{Implementation}
The Feedback LED is a component found on the LPC4088 board and hardwired. It was used to give feedback information on the operation of the system through the different color indication emitted by the LED itself. The LED driver was used to initialize the fucntionality as well as to set the respective color wanted to be diplayed. The led set fucntion accepted 3 int parameters indicating the different colors being red, blue and green. These colors can be set with a 1 or not set with a 0, this value being an int is boolean and float values will be assumed to be a one. If more than one of the colors are switched on then a mix of the two colors will be emitted.\\

The following light used are as follows:
\begin{itemize}
   \item NO LIGHT - If the LED is switched off or not light is being emitted. This indicates that the system is perfoming in the default decoding state without any flags set, that is auto scrolling off and adc value off.
   
   \item BLUE - Previously mentioned, the blue light idication on the LED shows that the auto scrolling feature/flag is turned on. This light is useful for debugging the EEPROM saving of the auto scroll flag, as it allows for easier visualisation of the state of the autoscroll feature.
   
   \item GREEN - The green LED indication is flashed when the user clears the screen using the switch center press. This light is valuable infromation to visualise the operation of clear being executed, also giving reason for a clear screen when debugging.
   
   \item RED - The red LED indication is used in the case when an error state is presented. The LED will flash red when the system detects two high or low freqeucies, not being able to distingush the respective signal. Along with the LED indication a LCD symbol '1' is presented to warn the user about this state. However, once again the LED flashing red is a more visual indication and useful for debugging.
   
   \item WHITE - The white light indicates that the user has entered the adc debugging state for the potentiometer. Here the user is able to adjust the respective potentiometer value to no have effect on results. The led indication toggles the white light when in this state and keeps a constant white light till the user exits this state. 
\end{itemize}

For swithcing between logical LED states the adc and auto scroll flags where used as parameters through the set functions. These functions where called during state switches and after every decode for logical completeness, ensuring the right led indication is indicated at all times.\\
